what happens when the Federal Reserve raises interest rates
there will be a rate hike , and `` the bull market '' is stumbling , bond yields will rise , and the economy falls into recession .
that we know .
what we do n't know is how long it will take until this time , and how long that will last .
specific to the economy , history shows little about time .
the recession came just 11 months after the first rate hike and for the whole 86 months .
the rigidity of the Federal Reserve in raising rates often , though not always , determines the reaction of the economy and financial assets .
that is why the administration of the US Central Bank has so insistently emphasised that investors should not focus on when it starts to raise rates , but on how much adjustment will take .
indeed , there are many variables in the game .
after all , however , market participants may find that all fuss around raising rates is exaggerated .
`` The first increase in rates by the Federal Reserve with the onset of the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as the signal of the end of an era of `` cheap money , '' '' said Julian Jessop , chief specialist at the international economy at Capital Economics , in a statement to clients .
on the contrary , we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal , but still low levels will be a seismic impulse that many fear .
that does not mean , however , that the consequences will not .
here 's a look at how some areas of the economy might react , depending on historical trends :
as the market has seen over the last month or so , waiting for a rate hike could lead to instability for a while .
when raising rates , however , the consequences are usually not that dramatic .
`` It does not seem that the proceeds of the shares are based on 12-24 months after the first jump , which , again , probably reflects the delay in monetary policy , '' Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent survey of the results of the Federal Reserve rate hikes .
if more concretely , the market for the last roughly 35 years is more likely to change sharply - about 14 percent - in the direction of rate hikes - remains fairly flat for 250 days after that ( average growth of 2.6 percent ) , then , at the rate of 500 days , returns to a normal state with an average yield of 14.4 percent over the last six cycles , according to a recent analysis conducted by Bob Long , a principal trading analyst at Nuveen Asset Management , published in Barron 's .
Deutsche said that the result for securities tends not to be more pronounced at the rate of rate hikes , and earnings from stocks are beginning to decline .
recessions are a fact of economic life , but raising rates often play by them .
in this case , the Federal Reserve is placed under conditions that have not existed before and can precipitate recession .
basically , gross domestic product will be almost at its lowest point in the lifetime of an increased rate .
according to Deutsche Bank , in 118 cases of the rate increase since 1950 only twice nominal annual GDP was below 4.5 % .
even though in the second quarter of 2015 , it was 3.6 percent , few believe that this is for a long time when it holds only 1.5 per cent in the third quarter , according to the Atlanta Fed .
raising rates on such an unstable economic background can be risky and raises the question `` will this time differently , '' reported Deutsche .
market participants are preparing to raise rates for the Federal Reserve all year round , with their view drawn up by the Federal Open Market Committee , which ends Thursday .
as long as many experts on strategists and economists believe the FOMC could approve a rate hike at this meeting , the futures trade speaks only about a 25-cent probability .
`` In our study , since 1950 , all the cycles of rate hikes before today were in the supercycle of an increased fiscal lever under GDP , overlapping of the peaks before recession , very quickly after recovery , '' the report said .
by contrast , it was an extremely slow recovery after the worst recession in the chosen period .
the current cycle at the moment - the longest that the Federal Reserve has been waiting for since the end of the last recession ; the record was 35 months ; it only lasts for 74 months and is not over yet .
fixed income has also become volatile while the market is expecting a rate hike , and this scenario is somewhat like the one that is being implemented for the shares .
the principal difference is that there will be an effect in the bonds than for shares when the Federal system changes its strategic course .
in the case of bonds , it seems that yields change the vector immediately after the first increase / reduction of rates in the cycle .
at the end of the cycle of rising rates , bond yields are immediately falling , '' Deutsche said .
strategy specialists from Charles Schwab believe a rate rise will result in the rates of long-term and short-term bond yields close , making the curve more flat .
