at the most anticipated for a few years , Fed chief executives will spend two days this week at a 27-foot-high table from the Honduran red tree , deciding whether to raise a key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade .
at one end , the richly decorated room for meetings with a height of two floors above them will be a wall image of the United States .
this card is a reminder that Federal Reserve Chair Jenet L. Yellen and her colleagues should put the country 's economic interests above all others .
the central bank received a double mandate from Congress : to maximize employment in the United States and hold stable prices here .
but since the Great Recession , the heads of the Federal system have recognized that there is a third , unsettling assignment : financial stability .
and that third order may prove to be an unknown factor in the near-predictive decision that will be announced Thursday , about whether the US economy is prepared to break away from the risk-free stimulus provided by near-zero short-term interest rates since the end of 2008 .
even though most of the data show a steady rise in the economy , recent turmoil in the world 's financial markets may hold up and so cautious Federal Reserve officials from adding volatility by raising the base rate on federal funds - even by just a quarter of a percentage point .
`` It is clear that the labor market and inflation will be the first and most important consideration , '' said Lindsey M. Piegza , chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co .
`` However , I think that if they were looking for a reason not to raise the rate , increased uncertainty around the world market is enough to give them an excuse to wait for further , '' she said .
there is no consensus about what the Federal Reserve will do , which itself provokes fluctuations in the financial market .
about half of economists recently surveyed by Bloomberg had forecast an interest rate rise this week .
financial markets , however , expect the Federal system to keep it off , with a key indicator showing only about a 30-percent chance of a rapid rise .
this could lead to a fall in the stock market if the Federal system raises the bid , provided those making the decisions do not soften the blow by the promise that the next increase will be an accident .
on Tuesday , the Dow Jones industrial average rose 228.89 points , or 1.4 % , to 16,599.85 .
the takeaway was provoked by expectations that the incumbents of the Federal system would leave a bid this week , '' said John Lonski , chief economist at Moody 's Capital Markets Research .
`` It will be a surprise if the Federal system increases rates at this point in time , '' he observed .
if the Federal Reserve 's leadership is so , `` they will have to go far in the approval of their strategy to keep financial markets in their hands so they do n't panic . ''
other experts objected that the rate rise could ameliorate financial markets because it would remove uncertainty over how the federal system would operate .
just a month ago , the Federal system seems inclined to raise a rate of 0.25 % this month , making the first small shuffle in a slow tightening of financial conditions that could prove the strength of the US recovery .
Yellen claimed in the spring and early summer that she expects to raise rates this year despite complaints from the Liberals about the need for greater economic progress .
although the emergence of new jobs in August has slowed , labor market growth has been stable this year .
unemployment has shrunk to 5.1 % last month , which is the lowest rate in more than seven years , and almost to the level that the Federal system considers to be full employment .
wage growth shows signs of acceleration .
and , while inflation continues to be below the target at the annual rate of 2 % , the Federal System Administration said that the key reason was the temporary effect of the sharp fall in oil prices .
the economy `` can cope with higher rates , and needs them , given the shrinking labor market , '' said Ian Scheferdson , chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics .
but financial markets around the world became shaking at the end of last month , after China devalued its currency .
the average Dow Jones industrial average fell by as much as 16 % relative to record highs in May , as investors feared that the slowdown in the Chinese economy could drag world growth .
the market has partially reinstated its position this month , and the Dow Jones industrial average is now about 10 % below high maths values .
for the Federal Reserve 's management , the outrage of the market complicates the uncomfortable calculations of the rate of interest rate increase .
`` In the absence of information on what happened in the financial markets and news of the weakness of the Chinese economy in the last few weeks they would have turned the screws on that meeting , '' said Steven D. Oprah , a senior researcher at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former Federal Reserve student .
it is now predicted that they will wait at least a month to get more control over the consequences .
`` There is greater uncertainty about what implications for the U.S. economy and they have almost no credible data after recent events in China , '' Oprah said .
the health of the world economy is not included in the main concerns of the Federal system , and technically it should not be taken into account when making these decisions .
but essentially the Federal Reserve has become a global financial authority .
the Central Bank 's impact in recent years has been huge .
one only hint from then-chairman Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Federal Reserve could `` mute '' its monetary expansion , sparked turmoil from markets around the world .
in a world where markets and economic systems are increasingly intertwined with each other , one might expect that Fed policymakers will not only monitor developments everywhere , but also consult with other central banks and experts to better understand the global economy .
their decision-making process is `` more an art than science , '' said Zakari Karabell , head of Envestnet Inc , a company that deals with global crisis management strategies .
Jeffrey Lacker , president of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond , Virginia , said this month that `` in the history of the Federal Reserve there were cases of overreaction on the financial market movement , which appears to be not related to economic principles . ''
Lacker , a member of the right voice of the influential Federal Open Market Committee , insisted on raising rates as the example brought the decision 1998-99 .
the Asian financial crisis has led the Federal system to lower its base rate by 0.75 per cent in three sessions , `` regardless of limited identifiable consequences for growth in the US , '' Mr Lacker said .
a year later , the heads of the Federal system cancelled these declines .
the Federal Reserve should put on the first place a concern for stability only in times of major crises , such as how the market crash in 2008 , '' said Adam S. Pozen , a former member of the interest rate committee at Bank of England .
the final panic and close did not come close to that level , he said .
`` You would , of course , do n't want to be in a situation when you are frightened of the rise in rates because the markets are experiencing a shock , '' said Pozen , president of the Peterson Institute for Peace Economics .
the Federal Reserve Act still has a dual mandate and does not mention financial stability , and until that changes , I do not think they should be ahead of events .
